1:{s:9:"owner_pic";s:0:"";}i:208;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391023520869209742";}i:209;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEunzlbA1aO";}i:210;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599252236;}i:211;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:855:"As part of my mother-in-law's downsizing, this pile of stationery ended up in my house. When I first looked at it I laughed and thought it must be some kind of performance art. As if you are writing a letter as an aspiring famous writer. And was it weird that I now possessed these? But a quick Google search yielded a much better story. Apparently this was a real place founded by Random House's famous publisher Bennett Cerf among its leadership. It was a mail order school that made $49 million in one year in the late sixties. That is, until the investigative journalist Jessica Mitford went and poked around and discovered it was all a house of cards.

But now I have more questions, including: did my mother in law attend? 

